# Step 1: Import libraries
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from functools import reduce
from matplotlib.colors import BoundaryNorm

# Step 2: Read the input files
shapefile = gpd.read_file('/content/Chiefdom 2021.shp')
df = pd.read_excel('intervention_data_new (1).xlsx')
df_population = pd.read_excel('/content/pop_chie_data.xlsx')

# Step 3: Filter rows and group by year
dfs = []  # List to store grouped DataFrames

for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Filter rows for the specific year
    df_year = df[df['year'] == year]

    # Group by 'adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3' and sum 'penta1_tot'
    df_grouped = df_year.groupby(['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], as_index=False)['penta1_tot'].sum()

    # Rename the 'penta1_tot' column to include the year
    df_grouped = df_grouped.rename(columns={'penta1_tot': f'penta1_{year}'})

    # Append the grouped DataFrame to the list
    dfs.append(df_grouped)

# Step 4: Merge all grouped DataFrames into one
df_merge = reduce(lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, on=['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], how='outer'), dfs)

# Step 5: Merge with population data
combined_data = df_merge.merge(df_population, on='adm3', how='left')

# Step 6: Merge with shapefile
data = shapefile.merge(combined_data, on=['FIRST_DNAM', 'FIRST_CHIE'], how='left')

# Step 7: Calculate penta1_coverages for each year
for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Calculate coverage dynamically with a fixed proportion of 0.04
    data[f'penta1_coverage_{year}'] = (
        (data[f'penta1_{year}'] / (data[f'pop{year}'] * 0.037)) * 100
    ).round(2)

# Step 8: Define years and the 'Blues' colormap
years = list(range(2015, 2024))  # From 2015 to 2023
cmap = plt.cm.Blues  # Blues colormap

# Step 9: Define normalization to consistently scale values between 0 and 100
bounds = [0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100]
norm = BoundaryNorm(bounds, ncolors=cmap.N, clip=True)

# Step 10: Loop through each year and create an individual plot
for year in years:
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    column_name = f"penta1_coverage_{year}"
    # Plot the data
    data.plot(column=column_name,cmap=cmap,norm=norm,edgecolor="black",linewidth=0.5,legend=False,ax=ax)
    # Set the title for the plot
    ax.set_title(f"Penta1 Coverage {year}", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
    ax.axis("off")
    # Add a custom colorbar legend
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
    sm._A = []  # Dummy array for colorbar
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax, orientation="vertical", fraction=0.03, pad=0.02)
    cbar.set_label("Coverage (%)", fontsize=12)
    # Save each figure as a separate PNG file
    output_file = f"penta1_{year}.png"
    plt.savefig(output_file, dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
    print(f"Figure saved as {output_file}")
    # Show the plot
    plt.show()
    # Close the current figure to free memory
    plt.close(fig)

# Step 1: Import libraries
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from functools import reduce
from matplotlib.colors import BoundaryNorm
import numpy as np

# Step 2: Read the input files
shapefile = gpd.read_file('/content/Chiefdom 2021.shp')
df = pd.read_excel('intervention_data_new (1).xlsx')
df_population = pd.read_excel('/content/pop_chie_data.xlsx')

# Step 3: Filter rows and group by year
dfs = []  # List to store grouped DataFrames

for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Filter rows for the specific year
    df_year = df[df['year'] == year]

    # Group by 'adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3' and sum 'penta1_tot' and 'penta3_tot'
    df_grouped = df_year.groupby(['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], as_index=False).agg({
        'penta1_tot': 'sum',
        'penta3_tot': 'sum'
    })

    # Rename columns to include the year
    df_grouped = df_grouped.rename(columns={
        'penta1_tot': f'penta1_{year}',
        'penta3_tot': f'penta3_{year}'
    })

    # Append the grouped DataFrame to the list
    dfs.append(df_grouped)

# Step 4: Merge all grouped DataFrames into one
df_merge = reduce(lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, on=['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], how='outer'), dfs)

# Step 5: Merge with population data
combined_data = df_merge.merge(df_population, on='adm3', how='left')

# Step 6: Merge with shapefile
data = shapefile.merge(combined_data, on=['FIRST_DNAM', 'FIRST_CHIE'], how='left')

# Step 7: Calculate dropout rates and coverage for each year
for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Ensure the columns are numeric
    data[f'penta1_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'penta1_{year}'], errors='coerce')
    data[f'penta3_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'penta3_{year}'], errors='coerce')

    # Calculate Dropout Rate with the condition
    data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'] = np.where(
        data[f'penta3_{year}'] > data[f'penta1_{year}'],  # Condition: Penta3 > Penta1
        0,  # If true, set dropout rate to 0.
        ((data[f'penta1_{year}'] - data[f'penta3_{year}']) / data[f'penta1_{year}'].replace(0, np.nan)) * 100  # Else, calculate dropout rate
    )
    # Round the result
    data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'] = data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'].round(2)

# Step 8: Define years and the 'Blues' colormap
years = list(range(2015, 2024))  # From 2015 to 2023
cmap = plt.cm.Blues  # Blues colormap

# Step 9: Define normalization to consistently scale values between 0 and 100
bounds = [0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100]
norm = BoundaryNorm(bounds, ncolors=cmap.N, clip=True)

# Step 10: Loop through each year and create individual dropout rate plots
for year in years:
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    column_name = f"dropout_rate_{year}"
    # Plot the data
    data.plot(column=column_name, cmap=cmap, norm=norm, edgecolor="black", linewidth=0.5, legend=False, ax=ax)
    # Set the title for the plot
    ax.set_title(f"Dropout Rate {year}", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
    ax.axis("off")
    # Add a custom colorbar legend
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
    sm._A = []  # Dummy array for colorbar
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax, orientation="vertical", fraction=0.03, pad=0.02)
    cbar.set_label("Penta dropout Rate (%)", fontsize=12)
    # Save each figure as a separate PNG file
    output_file = f"penta_dropout_rate_{year}.png"
    plt.savefig(output_file, dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
    print(f"Figure saved as {output_file}")
    # Show the plot
    plt.show()
    # Close the current figure to free memory
    plt.close(fig)

df = pd.read_excel('intervention_data_new (1).xlsx')
df_population = pd.read_excel('/content/pop_chie_data.xlsx')

# Step 3: Filter rows and group by year
dfs = []  # List to store grouped DataFrames

for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Filter rows for the specific year
    df_year = df[df['year'] == year]

    # Group by 'adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3' and sum 'penta1_tot' and 'penta3_tot'
    df_grouped = df_year.groupby(['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], as_index=False).agg({
        'ipti1_tot': 'sum',
        'ipti3_tot': 'sum'
    })

    # Rename columns to include the year
    df_grouped = df_grouped.rename(columns={
        'ipti1_tot': f'ipti1_{year}',
        'ipti3_tot': f'ipti3_{year}'
    })

    # Append the grouped DataFrame to the list
    dfs.append(df_grouped)

# Step 4: Merge all grouped DataFrames into one
df_merge = reduce(lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, on=['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], how='outer'), dfs)

# Step 5: Merge with population data
combined_data = df_merge.merge(df_population, on='adm3', how='left')

# Step 6: Merge with shapefile
data = shapefile.merge(combined_data, on=['FIRST_DNAM', 'FIRST_CHIE'], how='left')

# Step 7: Calculate dropout rates and coverage for each year
for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Ensure the columns are numeric
    data[f'ipti1_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'ipti1_{year}'], errors='raise')
    data[f'ipti3_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'ipti3_{year}'], errors='raise')

    # Calculate Dropout Rate with the condition
    data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'] = np.where(
        data[f'ipti3_{year}'] > data[f'ipti1_{year}'],
        0,  # If true, set dropout rate to 0.
        ((data[f'ipti1_{year}'] - data[f'ipti3_{year}']) / data[f'ipti1_{year}'].replace(0, np.nan)) * 100  # Else, calculate dropout rate

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    column_name = f"dropout_rate_{year}"
    # Plot the data
    data.plot(column=column_name, cmap=cmap, norm=norm, edgecolor="black", linewidth=0.5, legend=False, ax=ax)

# Step 1: Import libraries
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from functools import reduce
from matplotlib.colors import BoundaryNorm
import numpy as np

# Step 2: Read the input files
shapefile = gpd.read_file('/content/Chiefdom 2021.shp')
df = pd.read_excel('intervention_data_new (1).xlsx')
df_population = pd.read_excel('/content/pop_chie_data.xlsx')

# Step 3: Filter rows and group by year
dfs = []  # List to store grouped DataFrames

for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Filter rows for the specific year
    df_year = df[df['year'] == year]

    # Group by 'adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3' and sum 'penta1_tot' and 'penta3_tot'
    df_grouped = df_year.groupby(['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], as_index=False).agg({
        'anc1_tot': 'sum',
        'anc8_tot': 'sum'
    })

    # Rename columns to include the year
    df_grouped = df_grouped.rename(columns={
        'anc1_tot': f'anc1_{year}',
        'anc8_tot': f'anc8_{year}'
    })

    # Append the grouped DataFrame to the list
    dfs.append(df_grouped)

# Step 4: Merge all grouped DataFrames into one
df_merge = reduce(lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, on=['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], how='outer'), dfs)

# Step 5: Merge with population data
combined_data = df_merge.merge(df_population, on='adm3', how='left')

# Step 6: Merge with shapefile
data = shapefile.merge(combined_data, on=['FIRST_DNAM', 'FIRST_CHIE'], how='left')

# Step 7: Calculate dropout rates and coverage for each year
for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Ensure the columns are numeric
    data[f'anc1_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'anc1_{year}'], errors='raise')
    data[f'anc8_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'anc8_{year}'], errors='raise')

    # Calculate Dropout Rate with the condition
    data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'] = np.where(
        data[f'anc8_{year}'] > data[f'anc1_{year}'],  # Condition: Penta3 > Penta1
        0,  # If true, set dropout rate to 0.
        ((data[f'anc1_{year}'] - data[f'anc8_{year}']) / data[f'anc1_{year}'].replace(0, np.nan)) * 100  # Else, calculate dropout rate
    )
    # Round the result
    data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'] = data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'].round(2)

# Step 8: Define years and the 'Blues' colormap
years = list(range(2015, 2024))  # From 2015 to 2023
cmap = plt.cm.Blues  # Blues colormap

# Step 9: Define normalization to consistently scale values between 0 and 100
bounds = [0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100]
norm = BoundaryNorm(bounds, ncolors=cmap.N, clip=True)

# Step 10: Loop through each year and create individual dropout rate plots
for year in years:
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    column_name = f"dropout_rate_{year}"
    # Plot the data
    data.plot(column=column_name, cmap=cmap, norm=norm, edgecolor="black", linewidth=0.5, legend=False, ax=ax)
    # Set the title for the plot
    ax.set_title(f"Dropout Rate {year}", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
    ax.axis("off")
    # Add a custom colorbar legend
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
    sm._A = []  # Dummy array for colorbar
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax, orientation="vertical", fraction=0.03, pad=0.02)
    cbar.set_label("ANC dropout Rate (%)", fontsize=12)
    # Save each figure as a separate PNG file
    output_file = f"anc_dropout_rate_{year}.png"
    plt.savefig(output_file, dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
    print(f"Figure saved as {output_file}")
    # Show the plot
    plt.show()
    # Close the current figure to free memory
    plt.close(fig)

# Step 1: Import libraries
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from functools import reduce
from matplotlib.colors import BoundaryNorm
import numpy as np

# Step 2: Read the input files
shapefile = gpd.read_file('/content/Chiefdom 2021.shp')
df = pd.read_excel('intervention_data_new (1).xlsx')
df_population = pd.read_excel('/content/pop_chie_data.xlsx')

# Step 3: Filter rows and group by year
dfs = []  # List to store grouped DataFrames

for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Filter rows for the specific year
    df_year = df[df['year'] == year]

    # Group by 'adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3' and sum 'penta1_tot' and 'penta3_tot'
    df_grouped = df_year.groupby(['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], as_index=False).agg({
        'ipt1_tot': 'sum',
        'ipt3_tot': 'sum'
    })

    # Rename columns to include the year
    df_grouped = df_grouped.rename(columns={
        'ipt1_tot': f'ipt1_{year}',
        'ipt3_tot': f'ipt3_{year}'
    })

    # Append the grouped DataFrame to the list
    dfs.append(df_grouped)

# Step 4: Merge all grouped DataFrames into one
df_merge = reduce(lambda left, right: pd.merge(left, right, on=['adm1', 'adm2', 'adm3'], how='outer'), dfs)

# Step 5: Merge with population data
combined_data = df_merge.merge(df_population, on='adm3', how='left')

# Step 6: Merge with shapefile
data = shapefile.merge(combined_data, on=['FIRST_DNAM', 'FIRST_CHIE'], how='left')

# Step 7: Calculate dropout rates and coverage for each year
for year in range(2015, 2024):  # Loop through years 2015 to 2023
    # Ensure the columns are numeric
    data[f'ipt1_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'ipt1_{year}'], errors='raise')
    data[f'ipt3_{year}'] = pd.to_numeric(data[f'ipt3_{year}'], errors='raise')

    # Calculate Dropout Rate with the condition
    data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'] = np.where(
        data[f'ipt3_{year}'] > data[f'ipt1_{year}'],  # Condition: Penta3 > Penta1
        0,  # If true, set dropout rate to 0.
        ((data[f'ipt1_{year}'] - data[f'ipt3_{year}']) / data[f'ipt1_{year}'].replace(0, np.nan)) * 100  # Else, calculate dropout rate
    )
    # Round the result
    data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'] = data[f'dropout_rate_{year}'].round(2)

# Step 8: Define years and the 'Blues' colormap
years = list(range(2015, 2024))  # From 2015 to 2023
cmap = plt.cm.Blues  # Blues colormap

# Step 9: Define normalization to consistently scale values between 0 and 100
bounds = [0, 20, 40, 60, 80, 100]
norm = BoundaryNorm(bounds, ncolors=cmap.N, clip=True)

# Step 10: Loop through each year and create individual dropout rate plots
for year in years:
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))
    column_name = f"dropout_rate_{year}"
    # Plot the data
    data.plot(column=column_name, cmap=cmap, norm=norm, edgecolor="black", linewidth=0.5, legend=False, ax=ax)
    # Set the title for the plot
    ax.set_title(f"Dropout Rate {year}", fontsize=14, fontweight="bold")
    ax.axis("off")
    # Add a custom colorbar legend
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)
    sm._A = []  # Dummy array for colorbar
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm, ax=ax, orientation="vertical", fraction=0.03, pad=0.02)
    cbar.set_label("IPT dropout Rate (%)", fontsize=12)
    # Save each figure as a separate PNG file
    output_file = f"iptp_dropout_rate_{year}.png"
    plt.savefig(output_file, dpi=300, bbox_inches="tight")
    print(f"Figure saved as {output_file}")
    # Show the plot
    plt.show()
    # Close the current figure to free memory
    plt.close(fig)
